name="source">I. Martin Isaacs <fr:link
type="local"
href="isaacs-2008-finite.xml"
addr="isaacs-2008-finite"
title="Finite Group Theory">Finite Group Theory</fr:link> Theorem 1.11</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> be an arbitrary <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-004O.xml"
addr="gr-004O"
title="P-Group"><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link> of a finite <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-000G.xml"
addr="gr-000G"
title="Group">Group</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be any <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-004S.xml"
addr="gr-004S"
title="Sylow p-subgroup">Sylow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P\subseteq  S^{g}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
