toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2060</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#379</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-379.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega =\{Sx\mid  x\in  G\}]]></fr:tex> be the set of <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-003I.xml"
addr="gr-003I"
title="Right cosets of a subgroup">right cosets</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Observe <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |=[G : S]]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is a Sylow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. We know <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> acts by right multiplication on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex>, and so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> acts too, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is partitioned into <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbits. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, there must exist some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbit <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>By the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-004G.xml"
addr="gr-004G"
title="Orbit-Stabilizer theorem">Orbit-Stabilizer theorem</fr:link>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is the index in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> of some subgroup. It follows that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|P|]]></fr:tex>, which is a power of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is both a power of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, so the only possibility is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|=1]]></fr:tex>. Since the members of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> are right cosets of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, we can consider <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}=\{Sg\}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Sg]]></fr:tex> is alone in a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbit, it follows that it is fixed under the action of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Sgu=Sg]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  P]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[gu\in  Sg]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  g^{-1}Sg=S^{g}]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P\subseteq  S^{g}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
